summary:
In logic, a predicate is a symbol which represents a property or a relation. For instance, the first order formula 



        P
        (
        a
        )


    {\displaystyle P(a)}

, the symbol 



        P


    {\displaystyle P}

 is a predicate which applies to the individual constant 



        a


    {\displaystyle a}

. Similarly, in the formula 



        R
        (
        a
        ,
        b
        )


    {\displaystyle R(a,b)}

 the predicate 



        R


    {\displaystyle R}

 is a predicate which applies to the individual constants 



        a


    {\displaystyle a}

 and 



        b


    {\displaystyle b}

.
